This way `count` is created the moment you call `new Test()` and will be remembered until the Object is destroyed. Variables have something called a &#39;scope&#39;. They can only be accessed in their scope and will only exist in that scope. Because you created `count` inside your `void doMethod()` method, it did not exist anywhere else. An easy way to look at the scope is by watching the brackets `{  }` your variables are only stored inside those brackets. In my solution the brackets for `count` are the brackets for the entire `Test` class. Thus the variable is stored until the Object is destroyed.

